# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-cognito
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-cognito/amazon-cognito] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Authentication is relevant to multiple fields.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In art, antiques, and anthropology, a common problem is verifying that a given artifact was produced by a certain person, or in a certain place (i.e. to assert that it is not counterfeit), or in a given period of history (e.g. by determining the age via carbon dating).
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In computer science, verifying a user's identity is often required to allow access to confidential data or systems.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] It might involve validating personal identity documents.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The *first* type of authentication is accepting proof of identity given by a credible person who has first-hand evidence that the identity is genuine.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] When authentication is required for art or physical objects, this proof could be a friend, family member, or colleague attesting to the item's provenance, perhaps by having witnessed the item in its creator's possession.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] With autographed sports memorabilia, this could involve someone attesting that they witnessed the object being signed.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] A vendor selling branded items implies authenticity, while they may not have evidence that every step in the supply chain was authenticated.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The *second* type of authentication is comparing the attributes of the object itself to what is known about objects of that origin.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] For example, an art expert might look for similarities in the style of painting, check the location and form of a signature, or compare the object to an old photograph.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] An archaeologist, on the other hand, might use carbon dating to verify the age of an artifact, do a chemical and spectroscopic analysis of the materials used, or compare the style of construction or decoration to other artifacts of similar origin.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The physics of sound and light, and comparison with a known physical environment, can be used to examine the authenticity of audio recordings, photographs, or videos.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Documents can be verified as being created on ink or paper readily available at the time of the item's implied creation.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Attribute comparison may be vulnerable to forgery.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In general, it relies on the facts that creating a forgery indistinguishable from a genuine artifact requires expert knowledge, that mistakes are easily made, and that the amount of effort required to do so is considerably greater than the amount of profit that can be gained from the forgery.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In art and antiques, certificates are of great importance for authenticating an object of interest and value.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Certificates can, however, also be forged, and the authentication of these poses a problem.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] For instance, the son of Han van Meegeren, the well-known art-forger, forged the work of his father and provided a certificate for its provenance as well.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Criminal and civil penalties for fraud, forgery, and counterfeiting can reduce the incentive for falsification, depending on the risk of getting caught.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Currency and other financial instruments commonly use this second type of authentication method.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Bills, coins, and cheques incorporate hard-to-duplicate physical features, such as fine printing or engraving, distinctive feel, watermarks, and holographic imagery, which are easy for trained receivers to verify.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The *third* type of authentication relies on documentation or other external affirmations.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In criminal courts, the rules of evidence often require establishing the chain of custody of evidence presented.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] This can be accomplished through a written evidence log, or by testimony from the police detectives and forensics staff that handled it.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Some antiques are accompanied by certificates attesting to their authenticity.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Signed sports memorabilia is usually accompanied by a certificate of authenticity.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] These external records have their own problems of forgery and perjury and are also vulnerable to being separated from the artifact and lost.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Consumer goods such as pharmaceuticals, perfume, and clothing can use all forms of authentication to prevent counterfeit goods from taking advantage of a popular brand's reputation.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] As mentioned above, having an item for sale in a reputable store implicitly attests to it being genuine, the first type of authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The second type of authentication might involve comparing the quality and craftsmanship of an item, such as an expensive handbag, to genuine articles.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The third type of authentication could be the presence of a trademark on the item, which is a legally protected marking, or any other identifying feature which aids consumers in the identification of genuine brand-name goods.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] With software, companies have taken great steps to protect from counterfeiters, including adding holograms, security rings, security threads and color shifting ink.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Counterfeit products are often offered to consumers as being authentic.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Counterfeit consumer goods, such as electronics, music, apparel, and counterfeit medications, have been sold as being legitimate.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Efforts to control the supply chain and educate consumers help ensure that authentic products are sold and used.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Even security printing on packages, labels, and nameplates, however, is subject to counterfeiting.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Products or their packaging can include a variable QR Code.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] A QR Code alone is easy to verify but offers a weak level of authentication as it offers no protection against counterfeits unless scan data is analyzed at the system level to detect anomalies.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] To increase the security level, the QR Code can be combined with a digital watermark or copy detection pattern that are robust to copy attempts and can be authenticated with a smartphone.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] A secure key storage device can be used for authentication in consumer electronics, network authentication, license management, supply chain management, etc.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Generally, the device to be authenticated needs some sort of wireless or wired digital connection to either a host system or a network.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Nonetheless, the component being authenticated need not be electronic in nature as an authentication chip can be mechanically attached and read through a connector to the host e.g. an authenticated ink tank for use with a printer.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] For products and services that these secure coprocessors can be applied to, they can offer a solution that can be much more difficult to counterfeit than most other options while at the same time being more easily verified.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Packaging and labeling can be engineered to help reduce the risks of counterfeit consumer goods or the theft and resale of products.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Some package constructions are more difficult to copy and some have pilfer indicating seals.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Counterfeit goods, unauthorized sales (diversion), material substitution and tampering can all be reduced with these anti-counterfeiting technologies.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Packages may include authentication seals and use security printing to help indicate that the package and contents are not counterfeit; these too are subject to counterfeiting.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Packages also can include anti-theft devices, such as dye-packs, RFID tags, or electronic article surveillance tags that can be activated or detected by devices at exit points and require specialized tools to deactivate.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In literacy, authentication is a readers’ process of questioning the veracity of an aspect of literature and then verifying those questions via research.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The fundamental question for authentication of literature is – Does one believe it?
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Related to that, an authentication project is therefore a reading and writing activity in which students document the relevant research process.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The documentation materials for literature go beyond narrative texts and likely include informational texts, primary sources, and multimedia.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The process typically involves both internet and hands-on library research.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] When authenticating historical fiction in particular, readers consider the extent that the major historical events, as well as the culture portrayed (e.g., the language, clothing, food, gender roles), are believable for the period.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Literary forgery can involve imitating the style of a famous author.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] If an original manuscript, typewritten text, or recording is available, then the medium itself (or its packaging – anything from a box to e-mail headers) can help prove or disprove the authenticity of the document.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] However, text, audio, and video can be copied into new media, possibly leaving only the informational content itself to use in authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Various systems have been invented to allow authors to provide a means for readers to reliably authenticate that a given message originated from or was relayed by them.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The opposite problem is the detection of plagiarism, where information from a different author is passed off as a person's own work.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] A common technique for proving plagiarism is the discovery of another copy of the same or very similar text, which has different attribution.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In some cases, excessively high quality or a style mismatch may raise suspicion of plagiarism.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The process of authentication is distinct from that of authorization.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Whereas authentication is the process of verifying that "you are who you say you are", authorization is the process of verifying that "you are permitted to do what you are trying to do".
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] While authorization often happens immediately after authentication (e.g., when logging into a computer system), this does not mean authorization presupposes authentication: an anonymous agent could be authorized to a limited action set.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Similarly, the establishment of the authorization can occur long before the authorization decision occurs.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] A user can be given access to secure systems based on user credentials that imply authenticity.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] A network administrator can give a user a password, or provide the user with a key card or other access devices to allow system access.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In this case, authenticity is implied but not guaranteed.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Most secure internet communication relies on centralized authority-based trust relationships, such as those used in HTTPS, where public certificate authorities (CAs) vouch for the authenticity of websites.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] This same centralized trust model underpins protocols like OIDC (OpenID Connect) where identity providers (e.g., Google) authenticate users on behalf of relying applications.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In contrast, decentralized peer-based trust, also known as a web of trust, is commonly used for personal services such as secure email or file sharing.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In systems like PGP, trust is established when individuals personally verify and sign each other’s cryptographic keys, without relying on a central authority.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] These systems use cryptographic protocols that, in theory, are not vulnerable to spoofing as long as the originator’s private key remains uncompromised.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Importantly, even if the key owner is unaware of a compromise, the cryptographic failure still invalidates trust.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] However, while these methods are currently considered secure, they are not provably unbreakable—future mathematical or computational advances (such as quantum computing or new algorithmic attacks) could expose vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] If that happens, it could retroactively undermine trust in past communications or agreements.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] For example, a digitally signed contract might be challenged if the signature algorithm is later found to be insecure..
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The ways in which someone may be authenticated fall into three categories, based on what is known as the factors of authentication: something the user knows, something the user has, and something the user is.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Each authentication factor covers a range of elements used to authenticate or verify a person's identity before being granted access, approving a transaction request, signing a document or other work product, granting authority to others, and establishing a chain of authority.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Security research has determined that for a positive authentication, elements from at least two, and preferably all three, factors should be verified.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Ownership: Something the user has (e.g., wrist band, ID card, security token, implanted device, cell phone with a built-in hardware token, software token, or cell phone holding a software token).
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Inherence: Something the user is or does (e.g., fingerprint, retinal pattern, DNA sequence (there are assorted definitions of what is sufficient), signature, face, voice, unique bio-electric signals, or other biometric identifiers).
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Historically, fingerprints have been used as the most authoritative method of authentication, but court cases in the US and elsewhere have raised fundamental doubts about fingerprint reliability.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Outside of the legal system as well, fingerprints are easily spoofable, with British Telecom's top computer security official noting that "few" fingerprint readers have not already been tricked by one spoof or another.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Hybrid or two-tiered authentication methods offer a compelling solution, such as private keys encrypted by fingerprint inside of a USB device.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] As the weakest level of authentication, only a single component from one of the three categories of factors is used to authenticate an individual's identity.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The use of only one factor does not offer much protection from misuse or malicious intrusion.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] This type of authentication is not recommended for financial or personally relevant transactions that warrant a higher level of security.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Multi-factor authentication involves two or more authentication factors (something you know, something you have, or something you are).
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Two-factor authentication is a special case of multi-factor authentication involving exactly two factors.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] For example, using a bank card (something the user has) along with a PIN (something the user knows) provides two-factor authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Business networks may require users to provide a password (knowledge factor) and a pseudorandom number from a security token (ownership factor).
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Access to a very-high-security system might require a mantrap screening of height, weight, facial, and fingerprint checks (several inherence factor elements) plus a PIN and a day code (knowledge factor elements), but this is still a two-factor authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The United States government's National Information Assurance Glossary defines strong authentication as a layered authentication approach relying on two or more authenticators to establish the identity of an originator or receiver of information.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The European Central Bank (ECB) has defined strong authentication as "a procedure based on two or more of the three authentication factors".
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The factors that are used must be mutually independent and at least one factor must be "non-reusable and non-replicable", except in the case of an inherence factor and must also be incapable of being stolen off the Internet.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] In the European, as well as in the US-American understanding, strong authentication is very similar to multi-factor authentication or 2FA, but exceeding those with more rigorous requirements.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The FIDO Alliance has been striving to establish technical specifications for strong authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Conventional computer systems authenticate users only at the initial log-in session, which can be the cause of a critical security flaw.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] To resolve this problem, systems need continuous user authentication methods that continuously monitor and authenticate users based on some biometric trait(s).
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] A study used behavioural biometrics based on writing styles as a continuous authentication method.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Recent research has shown the possibility of using smartphones sensors and accessories to extract some behavioral attributes such as touch dynamics, keystroke dynamics and gait recognition.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] These attributes are known as behavioral biometrics and could be used to verify or identify users implicitly and continuously on smartphones.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The authentication systems that have been built based on these behavioral biometric traits are known as active or continuous authentication systems.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The term digital authentication, also known as electronic authentication or e-authentication, refers to a group of processes where the confidence for user identities is established and presented via electronic methods to an information system.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] The digital authentication process creates technical challenges because of the need to authenticate individuals or entities remotely over a network.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Authentication – After becoming a subscriber, the user receives an authenticator e.g., a token and credentials, such as a user name.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] He or she is then permitted to perform online transactions within an authenticated session with a relying party, where they must provide proof that he or she possesses one or more authenticators.
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Life-cycle maintenance – the CSP is charged with the task of maintaining the user's credential over the course of its lifetime, while the subscriber is responsible for maintaining his or her authenticator(s).
[src:aws-cognito/authentication] Extra identity factors can be required to authenticate each party's identity.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:aws-cognito/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:aws-cognito/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID standard provides a framework for the communication that must take place between the identity provider and the OpenID acceptor (the "relying party").
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] An extension to the standard (the OpenID Attribute Exchange) facilitates the transfer of user attributes, such as name and gender, from the OpenID identity provider to the relying party (each relying party may request a different set of attributes, depending on its requirements).
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID protocol does not rely on a central authority to authenticate a user's identity.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Moreover, neither services nor the OpenID standard may mandate a specific means by which to authenticate users, allowing for approaches ranging from the common (such as passwords) to the novel (such as smart cards or biometrics).
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The final version of OpenID is OpenID 2.0, finalized and published in December 2007.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The term *OpenID* may also refer to an identifier as specified in the OpenID standard; these identifiers take the form of a unique Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), and are managed by some "OpenID provider" that handles authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Facebook did use OpenID in the past, but moved to Facebook Connect.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Blogger also used OpenID, but since May 2018 no longer supports it.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID is a decentralized authentication protocol that allows users to authenticate with multiple websites using a single set of credentials, eliminating the need for separate usernames and passwords for each website.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID authenticates a user with an identity provider (IdP), who then provides the user with a unique identifier (called an OpenID).
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] This identifier can then be used to authenticate the user with any website that supports OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] When a user visits a website that supports OpenID authentication, the website will redirect the user to their chosen IdP.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The IdP will then prompt the user to authenticate themselves (e.g., by entering a username and password).
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Once the user is authenticated, the IdP will generate an OpenID and send it back to the website.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The website can then use this OpenID to authenticate the user without needing to know their actual credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID is built on top of several existing standards, including HTTP, HTML, and XML.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID relies on a number of technologies, including a discovery mechanism that allows websites to find the IdP associated with a particular OpenID, as well as security mechanisms to protect against phishing and other attacks.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] One of the key benefits of OpenID is that it allows users to control their own identity information, rather than relying on individual websites to store and manage their login credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] This can be particularly important in cases where websites are vulnerable to security breaches or where users are concerned about the privacy of their personal information.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID has been widely adopted by a number of large websites and service providers, including Google, Yahoo!, and PayPal.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The protocol is also used by a number of open source projects and frameworks, including Ruby on Rails and Django.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The end user interacts with a relying party (such as a website) that provides an option to specify an OpenID for the purposes of authentication; an end user typically has previously registered an OpenID (e.g.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] `alice.openid.example.org`) with an OpenID provider (e.g.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The relying party typically transforms the OpenID into a canonical URL form (e.g.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The `checkid_immediate` mode can fall back to the `checkid_setup` mode if the operation cannot be automated.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] First, the relying party and the OpenID provider (optionally) establish a shared secret, referenced by an *associate handle*, which the relying party then stores.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] If using the `checkid_setup` mode, the relying party redirects the end user's user-agent to the OpenID provider so the end user can authenticate directly with the OpenID provider.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The method of authentication may vary, but typically, an OpenID provider prompts the end user for a password or some cryptographic token, and then asks whether the end user trusts the relying party to receive the necessary identity details.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] If the end user declines the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party with a message indicating that authentication was rejected; the relying party in turn refuses to authenticate the end user.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] If the end user accepts the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party along with the end user's credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] That relying party must then confirm that the credentials really came from the OpenID provider.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In contrast, a *stateless* or *dumb* relying party must make one more background request (`check_authentication`) to ensure that the data indeed came from the OpenID provider.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] After the OpenID has been verified, authentication is considered successful and the end user is considered logged into the relying party under the identity specified by the given OpenID (e.g.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The relying party typically then stores the end user's OpenID along with the end user's other session information.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] To obtain an OpenID-enabled URL that can be used to log into OpenID-enabled websites, a user registers an OpenID identifier with an identity provider.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Identity providers offer the ability to register a URL (typically a third-level domain, e.g. username.example.com) that will automatically be configured with OpenID authentication service.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Once they have registered an OpenID, a user can also use an existing URL under their own control (such as a blog or home page) as an alias or "delegated identity".
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] They simply insert the appropriate OpenID tags in the HTML or serve a Yadis document.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Starting with OpenID Authentication 2.0 (and some 1.1 implementations), there are two types of identifiers that can be used with OpenID: URLs and XRIs.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] XRIs are a new form of Internet identifier designed specifically for cross-domain digital identity.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] For example, XRIs come in two forms—i-names and i-numbers—that are usually registered simultaneously as synonyms.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] I-names are reassignable (like domain names), while i-numbers are never reassigned.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] When an XRI i-name is used as an OpenID identifier, it is immediately resolved to the synonymous i-number (the CanonicalID element of the XRDS document).
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] This i-number is the OpenID identifier stored by the relying party.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In this way, both the user and the relying party are protected from the end user's OpenID identity ever being taken over by another party as can happen with a URL based on a reassignable DNS name.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation (OIDF) promotes and enhances the OpenID community and technologies.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OIDF is a non-profit international standards development organization of individual developers, government agencies and companies who wish to promote and protect OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation was formed in June 2007 and serves as a public trust organization representing an open community of developers, vendors and users.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OIDF assists the community by providing needed infrastructure and help in promoting and supporting adoption of OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] This includes managing intellectual property and trade marks as well a fostering viral growth and global participation in OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OIDF is a global organization to promote digital identity and to encourage the further adoption of OpenID, the OIDF has encouraged the creation of member chapters.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Member chapters are officially part of the Foundation and work within their own constituency to support the development and adoption of OpenID as a framework for user-centric identity on the internet.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OIDF ensures that OpenID specifications are freely implementable therefore the OIDF requires all contributors to sign a contribution agreement.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] This agreement both grants a copyright license to the Foundation to publish the collective specifications and includes a patent non-assertion agreement.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The non-assertion agreement states that the contributor will not sue someone for implementing OpenID specifications.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID trademark in the United States was assigned to the OpenID Foundation in March 2008.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] It had been registered by NetMesh Inc. before the OpenID Foundation was operational.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In Europe, as of August 31, 2007, the OpenID trademark is registered to the OpenID Europe Foundation.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID logo was designed by Randy "ydnar" Reddig, who in 2005 had expressed plans to transfer the rights to an OpenID organization.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Sun Microsystems, VeriSign and a number of smaller companies involved in OpenID have issued patent non-assertion covenants covering OpenID 1.1 specifications.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The covenants state that the companies will not assert any of their patents against OpenID implementations and will revoke their promises from anyone who threatens, or asserts, patents against OpenID implementors.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In March, 2012, a research paper reported two generic security issues in OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Both issues allow an attacker to sign in to a victim's relying party accounts.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] For the first issue, OpenID and Google (an Identity Provider of OpenID) both published security advisories to address it.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Google's advisory says "An attacker could forge an OpenID request that doesn't ask for the user's email address, and then insert an unsigned email address into the IdPs response.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] If the attacker relays this response to a website that doesn't notice that this attribute is unsigned, the website may be tricked into logging the attacker in to any local account." The research paper claims that many popular websites have been confirmed vulnerable, including Yahoo!
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Mail, smartsheet.com, Zoho, manymoon.com, diigo.com.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The researchers have notified the affected parties, who have then fixed their vulnerable code.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] For the second issue, the paper called it "Data Type Confusion Logic Flaw", which also allows attackers to sign in to victims' RP accounts.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Google and PayPal were initially confirmed vulnerable.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID published a vulnerability report on the flaw.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The report says Google and PayPal have applied fixes, and suggest other OpenID vendors to check their implementations.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Some observers have suggested that OpenID has security weaknesses and may prove vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] For example, a malicious relaying party may forward the end user to a bogus identity provider authentication page asking that end user to input their credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] On completion of this, the malicious party (who in this case also controls the bogus authentication page) could then have access to the end user's account with the identity provider, and then use that end user's OpenID to log into other services.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In an attempt to combat possible phishing attacks, some OpenID providers mandate that the end user needs to be authenticated with them prior to an attempt to authenticate with the relying party.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] This relies on the end user knowing the policy of the identity provider.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Other security issues identified with OpenID involve lack of privacy and failure to address the trust problem.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] However, this problem is not unique to OpenID and is simply the state of the Internet as commonly used.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The Identity Provider does, however, get a log of your OpenID logins; they know when you logged into what website, making cross-site tracking much easier.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] A compromised OpenID account is also likely to be a more serious breach of privacy than a compromised account on a single site.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Another important vulnerability is present in the last step in the authentication scheme when TLS/SSL are not used: the redirect-URL from the identity provider to the relying party.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The problem with this redirect is the fact that anyone who can obtain this URL (e.g. by sniffing the wire) can replay it and get logged into the site as the victim user.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Some of the identity providers use nonces (a number used just once) to allow a user to log into the site once and fail all the consecutive attempts.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The nonce solution works if the user is the first one to use the URL.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] However, a fast attacker who is sniffing the wire can obtain the URL and immediately reset a user's TCP connection (as an attacker is sniffing the wire and knows the required TCP sequence numbers) and then execute the replay attack as described above.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Thus nonces only protect against passive attackers, but cannot prevent active attackers from executing the replay attack.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Use of TLS/SSL in the authentication process can significantly reduce this risk.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] On May 1, 2014, a bug dubbed "Covert Redirect related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" was disclosed.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] It was discovered by mathematics doctoral student Wang Jing at the School of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The announcement of OpenID is: "'Covert Redirect', publicized in May 2014, is an instance of attackers using open redirectors – a well-known threat, with well-known means of prevention.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] "The general consensus, so far, is that Covert Redirect is not as bad, but still a threat.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] A patch was not immediately made available.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Ori Eisen, founder, chairman and chief innovation officer at 41st Parameter told Sue Marquette Poremba, "In any distributed system, we are counting of the good nature of the participants to do the right thing.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In cases like OAuth and OpenID, the distribution is so vast that it is unreasonable to expect each and every website to patch up in the near future".
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The original OpenID authentication protocol was developed in May 2005 by Brad Fitzpatrick, creator of popular community website LiveJournal, while working at Six Apart.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Initially referred to as Yadis (an acronym for "Yet another distributed identity system"), it was named OpenID after the openid.net domain name was given to Six Apart to use for the project.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID support was soon implemented on LiveJournal and fellow LiveJournal engine community DeadJournal for blog post comments and quickly gained attention in the digital identity community.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Web developer JanRain was an early supporter of OpenID, providing OpenID software libraries and expanding its business around OpenID-based services.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In late June, discussions started between OpenID users and developers from enterprise software company NetMesh, leading to collaboration on interoperability between OpenID and NetMesh's similar Light-weight Identity (LID) protocol.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The direct result of the collaboration was the Yadis discovery protocol, adopting the name originally used for OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The new Yadis was announced on October 24, 2005.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] After a discussion at the 2005 Internet Identity Workshop a few days later, XRI/i-names developers joined the Yadis project, contributing their Extensible Resource Descriptor Sequence (XRDS) format for utilization in the protocol.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In December, developers at Sxip Identity began discussions with the OpenID/Yadis community after announcing a shift in the development of version 2.0 of its Simple Extensible Identity Protocol (SXIP) to URL-based identities like LID and OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In March 2006, JanRain developed a Simple Registration (SREG) extension for OpenID enabling primitive profile-exchange and in April submitted a proposal to formalize extensions to OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The same month, work had also begun on incorporating full XRI support into OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Around early May, key OpenID developer David Recordon left Six Apart, joining VeriSign to focus more on digital identity and guidance for the OpenID spec.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] By early June, the major differences between the SXIP 2.0 and OpenID projects were resolved with the agreement to support multiple personas in OpenID by submission of an identity provider URL rather than a full identity URL.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Late in 2006, a ZDNet opinion piece made the case for OpenID to users, web site operators and entrepreneurs.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] On January 31, 2007, Symantec announced support for OpenID in its Identity Initiative products and services.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] A week later, on February 6 Microsoft made a joint announcement with JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign to collaborate on interoperability between OpenID and Microsoft's Windows CardSpace digital identity platform, with particular focus on developing a phishing-resistant authentication solution for OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] As part of the collaboration, Microsoft pledged to support OpenID in its future identity server products and JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign pledged to add support for Microsoft's Information Card profile to their future identity solutions.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In mid-February, AOL announced that an experimental OpenID provider service was functional for all AOL and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) accounts.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In May, Sun Microsystems began working with the OpenID community, announcing an OpenID program, as well as entering a non-assertion covenant with the OpenID community, pledging not to assert any of its patents against implementations of OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In June, OpenID leadership formed the OpenID Foundation, an Oregon-based public benefit corporation for managing the OpenID brand and property.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The same month, an independent OpenID Europe Foundation was formed in Belgium by Snorri Giorgetti.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] By early December, non-assertion agreements were collected by the major contributors to the protocol and the final OpenID Authentication 2.0 and OpenID Attribute Exchange 1.0 specifications were ratified on December 5.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In mid-January 2008, Yahoo! announced initial OpenID 2.0 support, both as a provider and as a relying party, releasing the provider service by the end of the month.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In early February, Google, IBM, Microsoft, VeriSign and Yahoo! joined the OpenID Foundation as corporate board members.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Around early May, SourceForge, Inc. introduced OpenID provider and relying party support to leading open source software development website SourceForge.net.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In late July, popular social network service MySpace announced support for OpenID as a provider.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In late October, Google launched support as an OpenID provider and Microsoft announced that Windows Live ID would support OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In November, JanRain announced a free hosted service, RPX Basic, that allows websites to begin accepting OpenIDs for registration and login without having to install, integrate and configure the OpenID open source libraries.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In January 2009, PayPal joined the OpenID Foundation as a corporate member, followed shortly by Facebook in February.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation formed an executive committee and appointed Don Thibeau as executive director.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In March, MySpace launched their previously announced OpenID provider service, enabling all MySpace users to use their MySpace URL as an OpenID.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In May, Facebook launched their relying party functionality, letting users use an automatic login-enabled OpenID account (e.g.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In September 2013, Janrain announced that MyOpenID.com would be shut down on February 1, 2014; a pie chart showed Facebook and Google dominate the social login space as of Q2 2013.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Facebook has since left OpenID; it is no longer a sponsor, represented on the board, or permitting OpenID logins.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In May 2016, Symantec announced that they would be discontinuing their pip.verisignlabs.com OpenID personal identity portal service.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In March 2018, Stack Overflow announced an end to OpenID support, citing insufficient usage to justify the cost.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In the announcement, it was stated that based on activity, users strongly preferred Facebook, Google, and e-mail/password based account authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID is a way to use a single set of user credentials to access multiple sites, while OAuth facilitates the authorization of one site to access and use information related to the user's account on another site.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Although OAuth is not an authentication protocol, it can be used as part of one.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The following drawing highlights the differences between using OpenID versus OAuth for authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Note that with OpenID, the process starts with the application asking the user for their identity (typically an OpenID URI), whereas in the case of OAuth, the application directly requests a limited access OAuth Token (valet key) to access the APIs (enter the house) on user's behalf.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] If the user can grant that access, the application can retrieve the unique identifier for establishing the profile (identity) using the APIs.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID provides a cryptographic verification mechanism that prevents the attack below against users who misuse OAuth for authentication.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Note that the valet key does not describe the user in any way, it only provides limited access rights, to some house (which is not even necessarily the user's, they just had a key).
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Therefore if the key becomes compromised (the user is malicious and managed to steal the key to someone else's house), then the user can impersonate the house owner to the application who requested their authenticity.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] If the key is compromised by any point in the chain of trust, a malicious user may intercept it and use it to impersonate user X for any application relying on OAuth2 for pseudo authentication against the same OAuth authorization server.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Conversely, the notarized letter contains the user's signature, which can be checked by the requesting application against the user, so this attack is not viable.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The letter can use public-key cryptography to be authenticated.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] Published in February 2014 by the OpenID Foundation, OpenID Connect (OIDC) is the third generation of OpenID technology.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] It is an authentication layer on top of the OAuth 2.0 authorization framework.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] It allows computing clients to verify the identity of an end user based on the authentication performed by an authorization server, as well as to obtain the basic profile information about the end user in an interoperable and REST-like manner.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] In technical terms, OpenID Connect specifies a RESTful HTTP API, using JSON as a data format.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] OpenID Connect allows a range of parties, including web-based, mobile and JavaScript clients, to request and receive information about authenticated sessions and end users.
[src:aws-cognito/openid-connect] The OpenID Connect specification is extensible, supporting optional features such as encryption of identity data, discovery of OpenID providers, and session management.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:aws-cognito/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
